               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-884" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-884" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-884" type="surname" value="FREEMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-884" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM FREEMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Suffblfr-street, Clerkenwell. I stopped Piddington at Smithfield-bars, on Easter Monday morning, at a quarter to eight o'clock, with a bundle under his arm, and an umbrella—there warn a sheet and blanket in the bundle—I asked him if they belonged to my mother—he said, no, they did not, and offered me the bundle—several drovers took him away from me, and he ran towards Charter-house-aquaie—I ran after him, calling "Stop thief"—he dropped the bundle—I took it up, and saw him stopped, without losing sight of him—the policeman came up, and I gave him the bundlfeftad the prisoner—this is the bundle—I knew the prisoner before. <hi rend="smallCaps">HENRY TODD</hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) The prisoner was given into my custody by Freeman, with these articles.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-885" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-885" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-885" type="surname" value="PIDDINGTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-885" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM PIDDINGTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prisoner Piddington's father, and live in Hemming's-buildings, Chapel-street, Clerkenwell. I took him to lodge with me—he got up on Easter Monday morning, and took three blankets and a sheet from his bed, and an umbrella—these produced are mine, and were safe when I went to bed on Sunday night—they were gone when I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184504070166"></xptr>
               <p>got up at a quarter past seven, and the street door left open—I know Pearson to be an associate of my son's—he lives in White Lion-street, about twenty yards from me—I have seen him about my house, but not on this morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-886" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-886" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-886" type="surname" value="DOUGHTY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-886" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DOUGHTY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Mr. Rosier, a pawnbroker, in Clerkenwell. I produce a blanket pawned by Pearson, for 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., on the morning the policeman came.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Pearson. Q.</hi> How do you know I pledged it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was there at the time—it was early in the morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-887" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-887" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-887" type="surname" value="PHILLIPS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-887" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN PHILLIPS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I apprehended Pearson on the Mon<lb></lb>day evening—I told him he had received a blanket from Piddington, and pledged it—he said yes, he had, he had lost the ticket and spent the money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Piddington put in a petition, stating himself alone to be guilty; that he gave the blanket to Pearson to pledge, to pay him</hi> 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. <hi rend="italic">which he owed, and that his father had been very cruel to him.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Pearson's Defence.</hi> I acknowledge pawning the blanket, but I did not know it was stolen.</p>
